ditions considered include Hinduism, ancient Greek religions, Judaism, Buddhism, Daoism, Confucianism, Christianity, and Islam. By applying trope theories, contributors reveal elements of these religions in and across their cultural contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aReligions. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology of Religion. 4aLanguage Arts : Linguistics. 4aPsychology : Psychology of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Psychology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aDoniger, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgge, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaskell, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Glen Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPathak, Shubha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPathak, Shubha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPatton, Laurie L, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlingerland, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Tony K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTweed, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUtriainen, Terhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhou, Yiqun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438445397423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438445397/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Pres